The fluorescence confocal microscopy (FCM) investigations showed the spatial distribution of CDs in planar aligned LC (Felix-2900–03) cells (Fig. 7
                        ). Aggregations were seen at 5.0 wt% concentration composite indicating that stable composites might be formed up to 2.5 wt%. The effect of dispersion of low and high concentration of CDs in LC could be understood with the help of a schematic representation shown in the Fig. 8
                        . These results suggest the optimum concentration of CDs in LC is required for the preparation of stable dispersion with enhanced electro-optical properties of LC in an environmentally friendly manner.

CQDs, when doped in NLC, have a tendency to introduce memory effect into NLC because of the amalgamation of CQDs in NLC (E48) which is demonstrated by Rastogi et al. 
                        [89]. The presence of volatile memory in CQDs-NLC composites was confirmed by dielectric hysteresis and electro-optical studies. Other electro-optical properties of NLC dispersed with CQDs were also studied which included birefringence, switching response time, and rotational viscosity. They employed three composites i.e., MIX1, MIX2, and MIX3, in which 0.1, 0.2, and 0.3 wt./wt. % of porous CQDs (∼4–6 nm) dispersed in NLC, respectively. These porous CQDs with sizes ranging from 4 to 6 nm and pore sizes of 1.5 nm were generated by single-step pyrolysis of oil palm leaf. The POM micrographs of pure NLC (E48) and their OPL-based CQDs composites revealed the phenomenon of Freedericksz transitions (Fig. 11
                        ).

From Table 2
                        , it can be seen that the threshold voltage was reduced for pure E48 as well as for its composites when the frequency was raised but it was found to be increased near dielectric relaxation frequency (2 × 105 Hz). If a lower electric field than the Recipe's dielectric relaxation frequency was applied, Vth decreased with increasing frequency as relaxation phenomena occurred. The impact of the electric field on the overall relaxation oscillations weakened as the frequency increased beyond 2x105 Hz and the threshold voltage increased. The capacitance versus frequency plots for pure NLC (E48) and composites gave information about volatile memory effects in them (Fig. 12
                        ). The authors reported that as ionic impurities were abundant at low frequencies (<100 Hz), their ionic effect dominated the capacitance. But as the frequency and voltage increased, their ionic effect decreased and then molecules were aligned in the field direction. The presence of residual charges caused the volatile memory effect. Because of its higher rotational viscosity and longer response time, MIX 3 showed the maximummemory when compared to pureNLC (E48) and other composites. The authors proposed that with all these improved properties, CDQs-NLC composites could be a suitable candidate for applications in phase shifters, photonic devices, supercapacitors, security and memory devices, and other fields.
